<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-762-534  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 762 534.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  July 30 1990 v4 n28 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Agency ADP buys in peril pending pact with Congress. (Office ofManagement and Budget threatens computer contracts; automated dataprocessing)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brewin, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Several government agencies may face severe budgetary cuts unlessCongress reaches an agreement on the 1991 budget.andP;  The Office ofManagement and Budget warns that this would affect the computerprocurement and modernization plans of most civilian agencies aswell as computer-related research projects.andP;  The programs thatwould be cut have a combined value of $12 billion.andP;  If Congressfails to reach an agreement on reducing the Federal budget,theGramm-Rudman-Hollings budget balancing law requires a $100 billioncut in 1991 evenly divided between defense and civilian agencies.andO;The 'automatic budget cut' may shelve or defer programs such asthe multi-agency Global Change Initiative, NASA's space shuttleoperations, the Federal Aviation Administration's $3.5 billionAdvanced Automation System and the Drug EnforcementAdministration's 1991 ADP modernization program.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Statute:   Balanced Budget and Emergency Deficit Control Act of 1985(interpretation and construction).andO;Topic:     Government ContractsFundingBudgetingResearch and DevelopmentUnited States. Office of Management and BudgetUnited States. CongressGovernment Agency.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>